\begin{itemize}
\item Structure description: Two order-statistic trees (balanced binary search trees with a \texttt{size} field at the nodes). One ordered by $x$ and the other by $y$. A pointer to the $(n/4)$-th element in the $x$-tree and to the $(3n/4)$-th element in the $y$-tree.
\item Implementation of \texttt{insert} and running-time analysis: Insert into both trees and perform \texttt{select} to update the pointers.
\item Implementation of \texttt{delete} and running-time analysis: Delete from both trees and perform \texttt{select} to update the pointers.
\item Implementation of \texttt{isCentric} and running-time analysis: Check the relation to the $x$- and $y$-values of the pointers.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Pre-processing:}
For each $x \in A$, define the key $k[x]$ to be the digits of $x$ sorted in ascending order. We can compute $k[x]$ for each element using quicksort on the digits in $O(L)$ time per element, for a total of $O(NL)$.
Now insert the elements of $A$ into a hash table under their key $k[x]$. If the key already exists in the table, append $x$ to the linked list associated with that key (each bucket holds a list that handles collisions, and each key stores another list containing all elements of $A$ with that key).

\textbf{Query Anagram($Z$):}
Sort the digits of $Z$ and look up $k[Z]$ in the hash table. The lookup takes $O(L)$, and we return the list stored under that key.
Alternatively, one may use a search tree instead of a table, but the query time becomes $O(L + \log N)$.

\textbf{(a).}
We use an array with the resizing algorithm taught in the amortization lecture: instead of waiting until the array is full and then moving everything at once to a larger array, we migrate the data in parts. Each time we perform an insert after the current array is more than half full, we reserve two positions in the new array and move two elements into it.

\begin{description}
\item[Insert:] As stated—initially allocate an empty array of fixed size (e.g., 4). For every insertion after the array has become half full, reserve two positions in a new array and copy two elements into it, so that the current array fills up, the new array is exactly half full, and is ready for us to switch to it. This is a constant number of operations, hence \(\mathcal{O}(1)\) worst case (insertions are, of course, insert-last).
\item[FindByKey:] Scan all array elements until the key is found or the array ends. \(\mathcal{O}(n)\) worst case.
\item[FindByIndex:] It is an array. \(\mathcal{O}(1)\) worst case.
\end{description}
